In Rust, the concept of "arc" usually refers to the `Arc<T>` type from the `std::sync` module, which provides a thread-safe reference-counted shared pointer. It allows safely sharing data across multiple threads, wherein each thread with a reference to the data increments the reference count; when no more references exist, the data is deallocated. 

When we talk about building a "custom arc" in Rust, it implies creating a custom implementation to support thread-safe reference counting.

Here's a basic outline of creating a custom arc:

1. Define a struct that will hold our reference-counted data. This struct will include a `data: T` field to hold the actual data, and a `ref_count: AtomicUsize` field, which will keep track of the reference count while allowing atomic operations.

2. Implement the `Clone` trait for the struct so that it can be easily cloned when a new thread needs access.

3. Implement the `Drop` trait for the struct to decrement the reference count when a reference goes out of scope, and to safely deallocate the data if the reference count reaches zero.

Here's an example of a simple custom arc implementation:

```rust
use std::sync::atomic::{AtomicUsize, Ordering};
use std::ops::{Deref, Drop};

struct CustomArc<T> {
    data: *const T,
    ref_count: *const AtomicUsize,
}

unsafe impl<T: Sync> Send for CustomArc<T> {}
unsafe impl<T: Sync> Sync for CustomArc<T> {}

impl<T> Clone for CustomArc<T> {
    fn clone(&self) -> Self {
        unsafe {
            (*self.ref_count).fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed);
        }
        CustomArc {
            data: self.data,
            ref_count: self.ref_count,
        }
    }
}

impl<T> Deref for CustomArc<T> {
    type Target = T;

    fn deref(&self) -> &Self::Target {
        unsafe { &*self.data }
    }
}

impl<T> Drop for CustomArc<T> {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        unsafe {
            if (*self.ref_count).fetch_sub(1, Ordering::Release) == 1 {
                std::sync::atomic::fence(std::sync::atomic::Ordering::Acquire);
                Box::from_raw(self.data as *mut T);
                Box::from_raw(self.ref_count as *mut AtomicUsize);
            }
        }
    }
}

impl<T> CustomArc<T> {
    fn new(data: T) -> Self {
        let boxed_data = Box::new(data);
        let boxed_ref_count = Box::new(AtomicUsize::new(1));

        CustomArc {
            data: Box::into_raw(boxed_data),
            ref_count: Box::into_raw(boxed_ref_count),
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    let data = CustomArc::new("Hello, world!");
    let cloned_data = data.clone();
    println!("{}", *data);
    println!("{}", *cloned_data);
}
```

This example defines the `CustomArc` struct and implements the `Clone`, `Deref`, and `Drop` traits. The `new` function initializes and returns a `CustomArc`. Note that the implementation above is minimal and may not cover all edge cases, but it demonstrates the basic idea of building a custom arc in Rust.

Creating a simple Gioui golang todos app involves several steps. Gioui is a modern UI library for Golang that uses GPU-efficient rendering techniques.

1. Install the Golang and Gioui library: Make sure you have Golang installed on your system, preferably the latest version. You can get it from [here](https://golang.org/doc/install). Then, install the Gioui library using the following command:

   ```
   go get gioui.org/cmd/gio@latest
   ```

2. Create a file called `main.go` and open it in your favorite text editor for Golang. Here's a simple todo app that you can use as a starting point:

   ```go
   package main

   import (
   	"gioui.org/app"
   	"gioui.org/layout"
   	"gioui.org/unit"
   	"gioui.org/widget"
   )

   func main() {
   	go func() {
   		w := app.NewWindow(app.Title("Todos"), app.Size(unit.Dp(320), unit.Dp(480)))
   		todos := make([]string, 0)
   		newTask := &widget.Editor{}
   		list := &layout.List{}
   		for e := range w.Events() {
   			if e, ok := e.(app.UpdateEvent); ok {
   				gtx := layout.NewContext(&e.Config, e.Queue, e.Size)
   				inputField := layout.Rigid(
   					func(gtx layout.Context) layout.Dimensions {
   						newTask.Layout(gtx, &e.Config)
   						if newTask.Submit() {
   							text := newTask.Text()
   							todos = append(todos, text)
   							newTask.SetText("")
   						}
   						return layout.Dimensions{}
   					})
   				todoList := layout.Flexed(1,
   					func(gtx layout.Context) layout.Dimensions {
   						return list.Layout(gtx, len(todos), func(gtx layout.Context, index int) layout.Dimensions {
   							text := todos[index]
   							widget.Label{Align: layout.Start}.Layout(gtx, &e.Config, text)
   							return layout.Dimensions{}
   						})
   					})
   				layout.Flex{
   					Axis:    layout.Vertical,
   					Spacing: layout.SpaceEvenly,
   				}.Layout(gtx, inputField, todoList)
   				w.Update(gtx)
   			}
   		}
   	}()

   	app.Main()
   }
   ```

3. Compile and run the app using the Gioui command:

   ```
   gio run main.go
   ```

The provided example creates a simple todo app with an editor for entering new tasks and a list to display the existing tasks. Feel free to extend and modify the example to meet your specific requirements.

To learn more about the Gioui library, check out the [Gioui documentation](https://gioui.org/docs/getting-started).

To create a JWT token to verify users in a Java server-side and jQuery client-side application, you can follow these steps:

Java Server-side (using Java's JJWT library):

1. Add the JJWT dependencies in your project. If you are using Maven, add this to your `pom.xml`:

```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>io.jsonwebtoken</groupId>
    <artifactId>jjwt-api</artifactId>
    <version>0.11.2</version>
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>io.jsonwebtoken</groupId>
    <artifactId>jjwt-impl</artifactId>
    <version>0.11.2</version>
    <scope>runtime</scope>
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>io.jsonwebtoken</groupId>
    <artifactId>jjwt-gson</artifactId>
    <version>0.11.2</version>
    <scope>runtime</scope>
</dependency>
```

2. Create a method for generating a JWT token given the user's information.

```java
import io.jsonwebtoken.Jwts;
import io.jsonwebtoken.SignatureAlgorithm;

import java.security.Key;
import java.util.Date;

public class JwtUtil {
    private static final String SECRET_KEY = "your_secret_key_here"; // Make sure to keep this key secret and secure.

    public static String generateToken(String userId) {
        Date now = new Date();
        Date expiryDate = new Date(now.getTime() + 86400000); // Set expiry date to 86400000 milliseconds (24 hours) later.

        return Jwts.builder()
                .setSubject(userId)
                .setIssuedAt(now)
                .setExpiration(expiryDate)
                .signWith(SignatureAlgorithm.HS512, SECRET_KEY)
                .compact();
    }
}
```

Replace `your_secret_key_here` with your own secret key. Remember to keep this key secret and secure.

3. Create a method to validate the JWT token received from the client-side.

```java
import io.jsonwebtoken.Claims;
import io.jsonwebtoken.Jws;
import io.jsonwebtoken.JwtException;
import io.jsonwebtoken.Jwts;

public class JwtUtil {
    // ...

    public static String parseToken(String token) {
        try {
            Jws<Claims> jws = Jwts.parser().setSigningKey(SECRET_KEY).parseClaimsJws(token);
            return jws.getBody().getSubject(); // Returns the user's ID as the subject
        } catch (JwtException e) {
            return null; // Invalid token
        }
    }
}
```

4. In your server-side logic, after verifying user's credentials (e.g., successful login), generate the JWT token and send it to the client.

```java
String userId = "12345"; // Replace with actual user ID after authentication
String token = JwtUtil.generateToken(userId);

// Send the token to the client-side via your preferred method, e.g., in the response body or as a cookie.
```

Client-side (jQuery):

1. Store the JWT token received from the server. You can choose to store it in a cookie, `localStorage`, or `sessionStorage`.

```javascript
var token = 'your_jwt_token_here'; // Replace with the JWT token received from the server
localStorage.setItem('jwtToken', token);
```

2. When making API requests to your server, include the JWT token as an Authorization header.

```javascript
$.ajax({
  url: 'your_api_endpoint',
  method: 'GET',
  beforeSend: function (xhr) {
    xhr.setRequestHeader('Authorization', 'Bearer ' + localStorage.getItem('jwtToken'));
  },
  success: function (data) {
    console.log('Data:', data);
  },
  error: function (error) {
    console.error('Error:', error);
  },
});
```

Java Server-side (continued):

5. In the server-side, when receiving an API request with the JWT token, validate the token and perform the requested operation. If the token is invalid, return an error response.

```java
String token = "your_jwt_token_here"; // Extract the token from the "Authorization" header from client request
String userId = JwtUtil.parseToken(token);

if (userId == null) {
    // Invalid token. Return an error response.
} else {
    // Valid token. Perform the requested operation.
}
```

In this way, you can create and verify JWT tokens in Java server-side and jQuery client-side applications.

Here is a Delphi code snippet for finding the intersection of two arrays ar1 and ar2:

```
var
  ar1, ar2, intersect: TArray<Integer>;
  i, j, k: Integer;
begin
  // Initialize input arrays
  ar1 := [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];
  ar2 := [2, 4, 6, 8, 10];

  // Initialize output array
  SetLength(intersect, Min(Length(ar1), Length(ar2)));
  k := 0;

  // Loop through arrays and find common elements
  for i := Low(ar1) to High(ar1) do
  begin
    for j := Low(ar2) to High(ar2) do
    begin
      if ar1[i] = ar2[j] then
      begin
        intersect[k] := ar1[i];
        Inc(k);
        Break;
      end;
    end;
  end;

  // Copy the intersection array to a new array with the correct length
  SetLength(intersect, k);

  // Print the intersection array
  for i := Low(intersect) to High(intersect) do
    WriteLn(intersect[i]);
end.
```

In this example, we initialize the input arrays ar1 and ar2 with some sample data. We then create a new array called intersect to store the common elements of ar1 and ar2. We loop through both arrays and compare each element, adding it to the intersect array if it is found in both arrays. Finally, we resize the intersect array to remove any empty space and print its contents.

Note that this implementation has a time complexity of O(n^2), which may not be efficient for large arrays. There are faster algorithms available for finding the intersection of arrays, such as using a hash set or sorting the arrays and performing a merging algorithm.

