Yes, you can use Firestore to fetch data and implement clean architecture. Here's a basic example of how you can set up the Firestore functionality and use ViewModel to manage your data.

1. First, add the Firebase and Firestore dependencies to your project's build.gradle file:

```groovy
dependencies {
  implementation 'com.google.firebase:firebase-core:19.0.1'
  implementation 'com.google.firebase:firebase-firestore:24.0.1'
}
```

2. Create a `TimePeriod` enum to represent the different time periods:

```kotlin
enum class TimePeriod {
    WEEKLY,
    MONTHLY,
    YEARLY
}
```

3. Create a `Report` data class to represent your report data:

```kotlin
data class Report(
    val title: String,
    val data: Map<String, Any>
)
```

4. Create a `ReportRepository` class to fetch the data from Firestore:

```kotlin
class ReportRepository {

    private val db = FirebaseFirestore.getInstance()

    fun getReports(timePeriod: TimePeriod, callback: (List<Report>) -> Unit) {
        db.collection(timePeriod.toString().toLowerCase()).get()
            .addOnSuccessListener { querySnapshot ->
                val reports = querySnapshot.map {
                    val title = it.getString("title") ?: ""
                    val data = it.data as? Map<String, Any> ?: emptyMap()
                    Report(title, data)
                }
                callback(reports)
            }
            .addOnFailureListener {
                callback(emptyList())
            }
    }
}
```

5. Create a `ReportViewModel` class to handle the data using ViewModel:

```kotlin
class ReportViewModel(private val reportRepository: ReportRepository) : ViewModel() {

    private val _reports = MutableLiveData<List<Report>>()
    val reports: LiveData<List<Report>>
        get() = _reports

    fun fetchReports(timePeriod: TimePeriod) {
        reportRepository.getReports(timePeriod) { fetchedReports ->
            _reports.value = fetchedReports
        }
    }
}
```

6. Finally, use the `ReportViewModel` in your activity or fragment to fetch the data and observe changes:

```kotlin
class MainActivity : AppCompatActivity() {

    private lateinit var reportViewModel: ReportViewModel

    override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState)
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_main)

        reportViewModel = ViewModelProvider(this).get(ReportViewModel::class.java)

        reportViewModel.reports.observe(this, Observer { reports ->
            // Update your UI with the fetched reports
        })

        // Fetch reports for a specific time period
        reportViewModel.fetchReports(TimePeriod.MONTHLY)
    }
}
```

This is a basic example of how to use Firestore to fetch data for a specific time period and utilize ViewModel for handling data in an Android app. You might need to adjust the data class and Firestore structure based on your actual data requirements.

