The following is a simple example of a C++ plugin for Dogot (Godot Engine). In this example, we will create a C++ plugin that adds a GDNative node that prints "Hello, C++!" when _process() is called.

Note that for this example, you must have the Godot C++ headers setup and GDNativeLibrary resource configured to link the plugin with Godot. An excellent tutorial for setting up a Godot C++ project can be found [here](https://docs.godotengine.org/en/stable/tutorials/plugins/gdnative/gdnative-cpp-example.html).

1. Create a file named `hello_cpp.h`:

```cpp
#ifndef HELLO_CPP_H
#define HELLO_CPP_H

#include <Godot.hpp>
#include <Node.hpp>

namespace godot {

class HelloCpp : public Node {
    GODOT_CLASS(HelloCpp, Node)

public:
    static void _register_methods();

    HelloCpp();
    ~HelloCpp();

    void _init();
    void _process(float delta);
};

}

#endif // HELLO_CPP_H
```

2. Create a file named `hello_cpp.cpp`:

```cpp
#include "hello_cpp.h"

using namespace godot;

void HelloCpp::_register_methods() {
    register_method("_process", &HelloCpp::_process);
}

HelloCpp::HelloCpp() {
}

HelloCpp::~HelloCpp() {
}

void HelloCpp::_init() {
}

void HelloCpp::_process(float delta) {
    Godot::print("Hello, C++!");
}
```

3. Create a file named `init.cpp` to initialize the plugin:

```cpp
#include <Godot.hpp>
#include <Engine.hpp>
#include "hello_cpp.h"

using namespace godot;

extern "C" void GDN_EXPORT godot_gdnative_init(godot_gdnative_init_options *o) {
    godot::Godot::gdnative_init(o);
}

extern "C" void GDN_EXPORT godot_gdnative_terminate(godot_gdnative_terminate_options *o) {
    godot::Godot::gdnative_terminate(o);
}

extern "C" void GDN_EXPORT godot_nativescript_init(void *handle) {
    godot::Godot::nativescript_init(handle);

    godot::register_class<godot::HelloCpp>();
}
```

4. Build this plugin by creating a `SConstruct` file and running `scons platform=<your_platform>`:

```python
import os

env = Environment()

# Change os according to your platform
env.Append(CPPPATH=['/path/to/godot-cpp/include', '/path/to/godot-cpp/include/core', '/path/to/godot-cpp/include/gen', '/path/to/godot-cpp/godot_headers'])

# Change extension according to your platform
env.Append(LIBPATH=['/path/to/godot-cpp/bin'])
env.Append(LIBS=['godot-cpp.<your_platform>.<debug|release>.<shared|static>'])

env.Append(CPPFLAGS=['-std=c++14'])

if os.name == 'posix':
    env.Append(CPPFLAGS=['-fPIC'])

env.SharedLibrary(target="hello_cpp", source=['hello_cpp.cpp', 'init.cpp'])
```

5. After building the plugin, create `GDNativeLibrary` resource in Godot project:

```
[gd_resource type="GDNativeLibrary" load_steps=1 format=2]

[ext_resource path="res://libhello_cpp.so" type="DynamicLibrary" id=1]

[resource]

path.unix = ExtResource( 1 )
```

6. Attach a GDNativeLibrary to a GDNative node in the Godot editor.

Now, when `HelloCpp` is attached to a Node in a Godot scene and the game is run, the console will print "Hello, C++!" once every frame. This demonstrates a basic Godot C++ plugin example that utilizes GDNative.

To generate a 2D Voronoi mesh with boundary clipping in C#, you can use a third-party library like the Delaunay-Voronoi diagram (2d) library. This library calculates the Delaunay triangulation and the Voronoi diagram of a given set of 2D points.

1. First, download the Delaunay-Voronoi diagram (2d) library from https://github.com/Biarity/DelaunayVoronoi.
2. Add it to your C# project.

Here's an example of how to use the library to generate a 2D Voronoi mesh with boundary clipping:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Drawing;
using DelaunayVoronoi;

namespace VoronoiMeshExample
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            // Define the boundary rectangle for clipping
            var boundary = new Rectangle(0, 0, 100, 100);

            // Create some random points within the boundary
            var points = GenerateRandomPoints(100, boundary);

            // Create the Delaunay triangulation and Voronoi diagram
            var delaunay = new DelaunayTriangulator();
            var voronoi = new VoronoiDiagram(points);

            // Generate the Voronoi mesh with boundary clipping
            var clippedEdges = voronoi.ClipEdgesToBoundary(boundary);

            // Print the clipped Voronoi edges
            foreach (var edge in clippedEdges)
            {
                Console.WriteLine($"Edge: ({edge.Point1.X}, {edge.Point1.Y}) to ({edge.Point2.X}, {edge.Point2.Y})");
            }
        }

        private static List<Point> GenerateRandomPoints(int count, Rectangle boundary)
        {
            var random = new Random();
            var points = new List<Point>();

            for (int i = 0; i < count; i++)
            {
                int x = random.Next(boundary.Left, boundary.Right);
                int y = random.Next(boundary.Top, boundary.Bottom);
                points.Add(new Point(x, y));
            }

            return points;
        }
    }
}
```

This example demonstrates how to create a 2D Voronoi mesh with boundary clipping in C#. It first defines a boundary rectangle for clipping, generates a set of random points within the boundary, and then creates the Delaunay triangulation and Voronoi diagram of the point set. The Voronoi edges are then clipped to the boundary and printed.

To render server-side-rendered content dynamically, you can use the `fetch` function to make an HTTP request to retrieve the desired content and then update the innerHTML of the target div.

First, create an API to serve your server-side-rendered content. For this example, let's assume you have an API endpoint at `https://yourserver.com/api/ssr` that returns the render HTML.

Create a JavaScript function to fetch the server-side-rendered content and insert it into the target div:

```javascript
// Function to get SSR content and insert it into the target div
async function loadSsrContent() {
  // Fetch the server-side-rendered content from the API endpoint
  const response = await fetch('https://yourserver.com/api/ssr');

  // If the fetch is successful, update the innerHTML of the target div
  if (response.ok) {
    const ssrContent = await response.text();
    document.getElementById('ssr').innerHTML = ssrContent;
  } else {
    console.error('Error fetching SSR content:', response.status, response.statusText);
  }
}
```

When you want to load the server-side-rendered content, call this function:

```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  // Load the SSR content when the page is loaded
  loadSsrContent();
});
```

This example will insert the server-side-rendered content fetched from `https://yourserver.com/api/ssr` into a div with the id `ssr`.

public class TableColumn {
    private String label;
    private String prop;
    private String slotScope;

    public TableColumn(String label, String prop) {
        this.label = label;
        this.prop = prop;
    }

    public TableColumn(String label, String prop, String slotScope) {
        this.label = label;
        this.prop = prop;
        this.slotScope = slotScope;
    }

    public String getLabel() {
        return label;
    }

    public void setLabel(String label) {
        this.label = label;
    }

    public String getProp() {
        return prop;
    }

    public void setProp(String prop) {
        this.prop = prop;
    }

    public String getSlotScope() {
        return slotScope;
    }

    public void setSlotScope(String slotScope) {
        this.slotScope = slotScope;
    }
}
